04062nam a22007095i 9789633865385DE-B159720220729113935.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220729t20221998hu     fo  d z      eng d  a97896338653857 a10.1515/97896338653852doi  a(DE-B1597)633513  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahucHU 7aHIS0370102bisacsh1 aFügedi, Erik, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Elefánthy :bThe Hungarian Nobleman and His Kindred /cErik Fügedi; ed. by Damir Karbić, Frank Schaer. 1aBudapest ;aNew York : bCentral European University Press, c[2022] 4c©1998  a1 online resource (184 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tCHAPTER I Introduction -- tCHAPTER II The Tripartitum and Reality -- tCHAPTER III The Elefanthy Kindred -- tCHAPTER IV Epilogue -- tNotes -- tList of Abbreviations -- tGazetteer of Geographical Names -- tList of Figures -- tList of Tables0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn an exploration of the life and customs of the Hungarian nobility, this book compares historical reality and legal literature on the example of one noble family--the Elefánthy kindred from northern Hungary (present-day Slovakia). The author begins by outlining the customary law regarding noble status, inheritance and marriage, as summarized in the famous code of Stephen Werbőczy (1514). He then compares these norms with the documentary evidence and establishes the fact that the legal literature differs in regard to social mobility and kindred solidarity. With this frame of reference in mind, the fate of the Elefánthy family is traced through several generations, enabling the author to make some general statistical statements on inheritance, the rise and fall of various branches, marriage strategies, and the "survival skills" of the kindred. In his summary, the author outlines some of the major avenues for further research, including the peculiar Hungarian form of retainership (familiaritas), and the relationships between noble families and between the nobility and local communities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  a16th Century.  a17th Century.  aHungary.  aMiddle Ages.  aNobility.  aSocial life and customs.1 aBak, János M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKarbić, Damir, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSchaer, Frank, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCentral European University Press eBook-Package 2013-1998z978311078055040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978963386538540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789633865385423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9789633865385/original  a978-3-11-078055-0  Central European University Press eBook-Package 2013-1998c1998d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK